subSection.paragraph:
Early blight disease (EB), caused by 

Alternaria alternata

and 

A. solani

, is a pre- and post-harvest disease in tomato (

Solanum lycopersicum
Mill.

) plants causing economic losses (
Kumar et al., 2013
; 
Moghaddam et al., 2019
; 
Wolters et al., 2019
). Symptoms of infection are characterized by black, or brown, lesions on leaves leading to defoliation and yield loss (
Thomma, 2003
). Although the disease is managed by application of fungicides (Odilbekov et al., 2019), identification of disease-resistant genotypes may be a sustainable, effective, and bio-rationale alternative (
Hashemi et al., 2019
; 
Moghaddam et al., 2019
; 
Nasr Esfahani et al., 2017b
; 
Nasr Esfahani, 2019
). Resistance analysis can be an effective part of an integrated EB management strategy but identification of EB-resistance sources in tomato has not been sufficiently explored (
Kumar and Praveen, 2019
).

Increasingly, molecular methods for assessing genetic diversity are needed to identify and improve disease resistance of tomato germplasms (
Monfared et al., 2018
; 
Periyannan, 2018
; 
Reynolds et al., 2019
). The Inter Simple Sequence Repeat (ISSR) marker is a highly polymorphic and reproducible method, and combines advantages of Simple Sequence Repeat (SSR), Amplified Fragment-Length Polymorphism (AFLP) and Randomly Amplified Polymorphic DNA (RAPD) methods (
Aguilera et al., 2011
; 
Kiani and Siahchehreh, 2018
). Although, use of DNA marker methods have revealed markers associated with disease resistance gene clusters, they have not been sufficiently extended to EB-resistance genotypes (
Adhikari et al., 2017
).

Several previous studies have highlighted that the expression of a number of defense-related genes was significantly altered by pathogen invasion (
Tsuda and Somssich, 2015
; 
Moghaddam et al., 2019
). Plants have developed a range of defense-related enzymes capable of initiating resistance to pathogens (
Meena et al., 2016
; 
Parvin et al., 2019
). Plants alter activities of reactive-oxygen-species scavenging compounds, such as Catalase (CAT; EC1.11.1.6), Peroxidase (PODs; EC1.11.1.7), Phenylalanine-Ammonia-Lyase (PAL; EC4.3.1.5), Superoxide Dismutase (SOD; EC1.15.1.1) and total phenolic contents (TPC) used against causal agents of fungal disease (
Benabdellah et al., 2009
; 
Hasan, 2017
; 
Awan et al., 2019
; 
Dey et al., 2019
). Also, in our previous study on resistant genes, 
S
1WRKYs and 7 PRs, and enzymatic activity of β-1,3 Glucanase and Chitinases, we have reported the effectiveness of these genes and enzymes in increasing resistance to 

A. alternata

in tomatoes, suggesting their roles in defense mechanisms or resistance (
Moghaddam et al., 2019
).

Of the 16 ISSR primers tested on 35 tomato genotypes, only eleven ISSR primers had high-quality amplification products and polymorphic bands. The UBC-815, UBC-820, UBC-867, and UBC-849 primers did not have any amplification products. The ISSR results showed that the total numbers of bands varied between 2 (UBC848) and 14 (INC3) with the average number of 6.18 bands per primer ranging from 100 to 950 bp in size. The UBC855, UBC880 and INC3 primers were found more reproducible and polymorphic. The average value of polymorphism percentages obtained in our study was 86.82%, with the lowest value for primers 430 (25%), UBC848 (50%), and the highest value (100%) for primers A12, UBC855, UBC818, UBC808, UBC840, UBC880 and INC3, suggesting a significant variation among the studied tomato genotypes. The polymorphic information content values ranged from 0.31 (INC3) to 0.50 (UBC840) with the mean value of 0.42. The marker index values varied from 0.33 (UBC848) to 4.45 (UBC855) with the mean value of 2.35 (
Table 2
).

The results obtained from analysis of ISSR primers, such as effective number of alleles (Ne), Nei’ s gene diversity(
H
), and Shannon’ s information index (
I
) are presented in 
Table 2
. The results showed that the highest values of effective number of alleles, Nei’ s gene diversity and Shannon’ s information index were obtained for UBC840 primer (1.89, 0.47 and 0.66, respectively). The lowest value of these indicators was detected in 430 primer (1.06, 0.06 and 0.13, respectively). The mean values of effective alleles, Nei’ s gene diversity and the Shannon index as a genetic diversity index were 1.46, 0.27 and 0.42, for all primers, respectively (
Table 2
).

Evaluations made on the basis of ISSR markers and grouping of genotypes based on the level of EB disease resistance, showed that the highly susceptible group (G1) exhibited the highest value in terms of band frequency, effective number of alleles, expected heterozygosity and unbiased expected heterozygosity (0.36, 1.34, 0.20 and 0.22, respectively) (
Table 3
). The lowest value of polymorphism percentage, band frequency, effective alleles, Shannon’ s information index, expected heterozygosity and unbiased expected heterozygosity were obtained for the resistant group genotypes (G5) (36.76, 0.28, 1.21, 0.19, 0.13 and 0.14%, respectively) (
Table 3
). The Nei’ s genetic distances between pairs of these groups were calculated based on the 63 analyzed bands. The highest value of genetic distance (0.05) was found between G5 and G1 (
Table 4
). Furthermore, AMOVA analysis revealed that the highest total genetic variation was within the grouped genotypes (97%), whereas the variance among these groups was only 3% (Table 5).

basis PCA (
Fig. 4
). Compared to the results of UPGMA analysis, 111Falat American and Roma (purple and yellow ovals, respectively) were scattered on the plot (
Fig. 3
). Based on the results of cluster analysis and PCA, Roma and 111Falat American as moderately resistant genotypes had the largest genetic distances from others, enabling them to be easily distinguished from other groups. In conclusion, using 2D and 3D basis PCA, 35 tomato genotypes were classified into five groups, largely in agreement with the five resistance levels of the genotypes (
Figs. 3–4
).

In the recent literature, resistance variation to EB disease was known to be mainly associated with genetic variation within the studied genotypes. However, there are limited reports on extensive evaluation for genetic EB disease -resistance in tomato genotypes (
Adhikari et al., 2017
; 
Nasr Esfahani et al., 2017b
; 
Nasr Esfahani, 2018a
). Characterization of genotypes based on ISSR markers has gained attention for genetic variation analysis (
Govindaraj et al., 2015
). In the present study, the UBC855, UBC880 and INC3 primers were identified as more reproducible and polymorphic primers with an average of 6.18 bands; 
Henareh et al. (2016)
also found that UBC855 and UBC880 were highly polymorphic primers.

The highest genetic distance obtained in our results revealed significant genetic differences of susceptible and resistant genotypes (
Monfared et al., 2018
). Clearly, the major genetic variations (97%) obtained within tested genotypes suggest the effectiveness of ISSR markers in identifying higher genetic diversity within genotype groups rather than between the groups (
Monfared et al., 2018
).

The pathogen strain ( KY322589 ) was isolated from infected tomato leaves. The isolate was cultured in PDA and incubated for 15 days at 24 ± 1 ◦ C, before induction of sporulation as demonstrated by Shahin and Shepard (1979) under cool-white fluorescent light with a 12-h photoperiod ( Foolad et al., 2000 ). Genotypes were screened for EB resistance. Inocula preparation was carried as described by Nasr Esfahani et al. (2017a) . The conidial suspension (10 5 spores∙mL 1 ) was sprayed 3 times in a 3-day interval at transplanting and mature stages, on the foliage, under 27 ± 1 ◦ C, 16-h photoperiod, and 65% relative humidity. Screening assays were performed at transplanting (6-week) and maturing (12-week) after transplanting. At 20 days after inoculation at both stages after emergence of symptoms, disease progress was evaluated. Disease severity was assessed based on infection percent (0–100) against the scoring scales of: 0, 5, 10, 25, 50, 75 or 100% ( Hayat Moghaddam et al., 2011 ;
Nasr Esfahani, 2018 a
, 2019). Controls consisted of plants in pots without inoculation.

The EB disease severity data were converted using Asin √x + 0.5 for homogeneity, and analysis of variance was performed using SAS (ver. 9.4, SAS Institute, Cary, NC) (SAS, 2004), and the means were compared using least significant difference (LSD). Statistical analysis was done by GenStat software (GenStat for Windows, 6th VSN International, 
UK
). Analysis of variance (ANOVA) was performed to evaluate the impact of different genotypes on EB disease severity. Pearson correlation analysis was also carried out to analyze the relationship among the tomato genotypes and response variability and cluster analysis of data was performed using SPSS software (
Ghasemi et al., 2014
; 
Hashemi et al., 2020
).

The PCR products were scored as present = 1 or absent = 0. Polymorphism levels and calculated by separating polymorphic bands from total scored bands. The Similarity for Qualitative Data (SIMQUAL) routine was used to determine the Jacquard similarity coefficient. A dendrogram with the Unweighted Pair Group Method with Arithmetic Average (UPGMA) algorithm was constructed using NTSYS software (ver. 2.1, Numerical taxonomy and multivariate analysis system, Applied Biostatistics, 
New York
, 
USA
). The distribution of genetic variation within, and among, groups, was detected using the molecular variance analysis (AMOVA) in GenAlEx software (
Peakall and Smouse, 2006
). Genetic variation indices, including effective numbers of alleles (Ne), Shannon’ s information index (
I
), Nei’ s gene diversity (
H
), percent of polymorphic loci (PPL), were estimated using POP-GENE software (
Yeh et al., 1999
). All data were in triplicate.

Biochemical data were analyzed with SPSS (ver. 16.0, Chicago, IL). Two-way ANOVA test was used for data analysis of variance between infected tomato and controls and mean difference analysis of the data was evaluated with LSD test (
Moghaddam et al., 2019
).
